339 9. (1) To combat problem gambling, video lottery game
340 operators shall allow players to be self-excluded from video
341 lottery game play pursuant to rules adopted by the
342 commission.
343 (2) Video lottery game operators may establish a
344 player rewards systems approved by the commission. No
345 player shall be required to enroll in a rewards program
346 offered by a video lottery game operator as a condition to
347 play video lottery games.
348 10. (1) Video lottery game terminals shall not
349 directly dispense anything of value except for video lottery
350 game tickets. Tickets shall be dispensed by pressing the
351 ticket dispensing button on the video lottery game terminal
352 at the end of any video lottery game play or series of
353 plays. The value of video lottery game terminal credits
354 shall be determined by the commission. Video lottery game
355 operators shall not be required to pay out coins for prizes
356 to be paid to a player having a value less than one dollar,
357 and redemption terminals shall not be required to dispense
358 coins. Any prize to be paid to a player having a value less
359 than one dollar shall be dispensed to the player from the

SB 862 19
360 redemption terminal in the form of a ticket, which may be
361 inserted into a video lottery game terminal for play. The
362 commission may adopt rules allowing redemption terminals to
363 allow a player to donate prizes to be paid to a player
364 having a value of less than one dollar to charitable
365 organizations.
366 (2) The maximum wager for a single video lottery game
367 shall not exceed four dollars. The maximum prize won from a
368 single wager for video lottery game play shall be no more
369 than one dollar less than the minimum amount required to
370 report gambling winnings from slot machines pursuant to IRS
371 Form W2G and IRS Form 5754;
372 (3) No more than eight video lottery game terminals
373 may be placed at the business premises of a video lottery
374 game retailer;
375 (4) The play, use, or operation of video lottery games
376 and video lottery game terminals shall not be advertised to
377 the public through any means including, but not limited to,
378 media outlets, social media advertising, direct mail,
379 broadcast media, telephone solicitation, billboards, or
380 other signage. The commission may adopt rules allowing for
381 limited signage to be displayed at a video lottery game
382 retailer's premises. The advertising prohibition contained
383 in this subdivision shall apply to all licensees including,
384 but not limited to, video lottery game manufacturers, video
385 lottery game distributors, video lottery game operators,
386 video lottery game retailers, and video lottery game
387 handlers. Notwithstanding any other provision of law to the
388 contrary, there is no prohibition or restriction on direct
389 or indirect marketing or advertising of video lottery games,
390 video lottery game terminals, or redemption terminals by
391 video lottery game manufacturers, and video lottery game

SB 862 20
392 distributors to video lottery game operators and video
393 lottery game retailers. Video lottery game operators may
394 advertise, promote, and market to players of video lottery
395 games and video lottery game terminals through player
396 rewards programs approved by the commission.
397 (5) Video lottery games shall not be played at any
398 time when the video lottery game retailer's establishment is
399 closed for business.
400 11. (1) No person under twenty-one years of age shall
401 play video lottery games or video lottery game terminals.
402 The video lottery game retailer shall be responsible for
403 preventing persons under twenty-one years of age from
404 playing video lottery games or video lottery game terminals.
405 (2) Video lottery game operators shall install,
406 maintain, and operate video surveillance systems within the
407 immediate area of the video lottery game retailer's
408 establishment where video lottery game terminals and
409 redemption terminals are located. The surveillance system
410 may also cover the perimeter of the video lottery game
411 retailer's premises. The video lottery game operator shall
412 maintain video footage for thirty days and shall, upon
413 request, provide such footage to the commission. Video
414 footage taken by the video surveillance system shall:
415 (a) Be deleted and expunged after the thirty day
416 period described in this subdivision; and
417 (b) Not make use of any facial recognition technology
418 or software.
419 (3) The commission shall adopt rules regarding the
420 investigation and enforcement of violations of law, rule, or
421 regulation governing the conduct of video lottery games in
422 conformance with established commission procedures, which

SB 862 21
423 may include fines, suspension, and revocation of licenses
424 issued by the commission.
425 (4) A video lottery game operator shall post a sign in
426 a conspicuous location where such video lottery game
427 terminals are located containing, in red lettering at least
428 one-half inch high on a white background, a telephone
429 contact number (1-888-BETSOFF) for the problem gambling
430 helpline, or other similar information as determined by the
431 commission. The commission may adopt rules for the
432 mandatory posting of signage regarding problem gaming,
433 underage gaming, and other consumer protection measures.
434 (5) Pursuant to rules adopted by the department and
435 the commission, a video lottery game operator shall be
436 responsible for:
437 (a) Paying prizes won from video lottery game play to
438 winning players;
439 (b) Collecting all funds from video lottery game
440 terminals;
441 (c) Depositing all funds collected from video lottery
442 game terminals into a separate bank account maintained by
443 the video lottery game operator to allow for monthly
444 electronic fund transfers by the commission and the
445 department all applicable adjusted gross gaming tax and
446 municipality and county administration tax;
447 (d) After such transfer to the commission and the
448 department, remitting to the video lottery game retailer its
449 share of net terminal income on not less than a monthly
450 basis. The video lottery game operator may thereafter
451 transfer its share of net terminal income to its business
452 operations account; and
453 (e) The commission may adopt rules allowing for the
454 division of net terminal income between the video lottery

SB 862 22
455 game operator and the video lottery game retailer on a basis
456 other than an equal division of net terminal income.
457 (6) A video lottery game retailer or operator shall
458 place a conspicuous warning label or sticker on each video
459 lottery game terminal at each video lottery game retailer
460 location in red lettering at least one-half inch high on
461 white background that reads, "WARNING: GAMBLING CAN BE
462 ADDICTIVE".
463 12. The adjusted gross gaming revenue tax shall be
464 imposed on adjusted gross gaming revenue. Video lottery
465 game operators shall collect and remit the adjusted gross
466 gaming revenue tax, which shall be deposited in the state
467 lottery fund pursuant to rules adopted by the commission.
468 The commission shall use and transmit such funds as follows:
469 (1) The commission shall retain an amount from the
470 adjusted gross gaming revenue tax necessary to cover direct
471 administrative expenses for the regulation and enforcement
472 of the video lottery game program that are not covered by
473 license fees or reimbursements;
474 (2) Subject to appropriations, all remaining funds
475 after administrative expenses and payment of prizes shall be
476 transferred to the lottery proceeds fund and shall be
477 appropriated equally to public elementary and secondary
478 education and public institutions of higher education. Ten
479 percent of such funds shall be appropriated to public
480 institutions of higher education workforce development
481 programs, and ten percent of such funds shall be
482 appropriated for construction and rehabilitation of public
483 elementary and secondary education facilities. The funding
484 provided for in this subdivision shall supplement, and not
485 supplant, any education funding otherwise appropriated by
486 the general assembly.

SB 862 23
487 13. The municipality and county administration tax
488 shall be imposed on adjusted gross gaming revenue. Video
489 lottery game operators shall remit the municipality and
490 county administration tax to the department. The department
491 shall distribute such funds to the municipality or county
492 identified by the commission pursuant to subdivision (15) of
493 subsection 2 of this section. The municipality or county
494 shall receive the proceeds of the municipality and county
495 administration tax generated by the video lottery game
496 terminals located within the jurisdiction of the identified
497 municipality or county to be used for providing services
498 necessary for the safety of the public visiting a video
499 lottery game retailer's location. All revenue owed to the
500 municipality or county shall be deposited and distributed to
501 the municipality or county in accordance with rules and
502 regulations created by the department. All the funds
503 deposited with any municipality or county shall not be
504 considered state funds and shall be deposited in the
505 municipality or county's general revenue fund to be expended
506 as provided for in this section.
507 14. All revenues received by the commission from
508 license fees and any reimbursements associated with the
509 administration of the provisions of sections 313.425 to
510 313.445, and all interest earned thereon, shall be used for
511 administrative expenses and shall be deposited in the state
512 lottery fund. Moneys deposited into the state lottery fund
513 from license fees and any reimbursements of commission
514 administrative expenses to administer sections 313.425 to
515 313.445 shall not be considered net proceeds under Article
516 III, Section 39(b) of the Constitution of Missouri. Subject
517 to appropriation, up to one percent of such license fees

SB 862 24
518 shall be deposited to the credit of the compulsive gamblers
519 fund created under section 313.842.
520 15. The commission may contract with a state law
521 enforcement entity to assist in conducting background
522 investigations of video lottery game license applicants, and
523 for the enforcement of sections 313.425 to 313.445.
524 16. The commission shall adopt rules for the
525 implementation of the video lottery game system authorized
526 under sections 313.425 to 313.445, including, but not
527 limited to, a designation of a distinct, designated area
528 within a video lottery game retailer's premises as the video
529 lottery gaming area that is divided from the primary
530 business operation area of the video lottery game retailer's
531 premises where all video lottery game terminals and
532 redemption terminals shall be placed and operated and all
533 gaming activity shall be conducted. Any rule or portion of
534 a rule, as that term is defined in section 536.010, that is
535 created under the authority delegated in this section shall
536 become effective only if it complies with and is subject to
537 all of the provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable,
538 section 536.028. This section and chapter 536 are
539 nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with the
540 general assembly pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay
541 the effective date, or to disapprove and annul a rule are
542 subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of
543 rulemaking authority and any rule proposed or adopted after
544 August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
